lso because the ‘education’ aspect is only a small part of what going to school is about. The social aspects are just as (if not more) important in helping a child develop into a well rounded person capable of functioning in the wider world. Keeping children in the bubble of the home environment may well do more harm than good. &#10;Of course there are many parents who choose to home school because they want to brainwash their children with extreme religious or political nonsense. I’m not saying this is the case here, but it’s certainly something that needs to be considered in the wider debate. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="901" language="en" documentId="745" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Valten78" date="07 January 2011 11:19am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/9049855" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="65" thumbsDown="0" origId="745" notes="" title="Why I home school my children"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="104"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="105" end="633"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="634" end="901"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>